{"id":"2103.09473","submitter":"Surjyasish Mitra","authors":"Surjyasish Mitra, Quoc Vo and Tuan Tran","title":"Bouncing-to-wetting transition for impact of water droplets on soft\n  solids","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1039/D1SM00339A.","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  Soft surfaces impacted by liquid droplets trap more air underneath than their\nrigid counterpart. The extended lifetime of the air film not only facilitates\nbouncing behaviours of the impacting droplets but also increases the\npossibility of an interaction between the air film itself and the air cavity\nformed inside the droplets by capillary waves. Such interaction may cause\nrupture of the trapped air film by a so-called dimple inversion phenomenon and\nsuppress bouncing. In this work, we systematically investigate the relation\nbetween air cavity collapse and air film rupture for water droplets impacting\non soft, hydrophobic surfaces. By constructing a bouncing-to-wetting phase\ndiagram based on the rupturing dynamics of the trapped air film, we observe\nthat the regime in which air film rupture is induced by dimple inversion\nconsistently separates the bouncing regime and the one in which wetting is\ncaused by random rupture. We also find that air film rupture by dimple\ninversion, in-turn, affects both the collapsing dynamics of the air cavity and\nthe resulting high-speed jet. We then provide a detailed characterisation of\nthe collapsing dynamics of the air cavity and subsequent jetting.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 17 Mar 2021 07:04:17 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 11 May 2021 08:59:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-05-12"}
