{"id":"2103.09733","submitter":"Mathieu Lamoureux","authors":"Mathieu Lamoureux","title":"Identification of neutrino bursts associated to supernovae with\n  Real-time Test Statistic (RTS$^2$) method","comments":"6 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":"A&A 654, A95 (2021)","doi":"10.1051/0004-6361/202141305","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE physics.data-an","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This paper proposes a new approach for the selection of low-energy neutrino\nbursts, such as the ones detected after a supernova. It exploits the temporal\nstructure of the expected signal with respect to the more diffuse background by\ndefining a \"Real-time Test Statistic\" (RTS) that would allow identifying very\nweak signals, hard to select using standard clustering methods. For a given\nbackground rate, the new method (RTS$^2$: RTS for Supernovae) increases signal\nefficiency while keeping the same false alarm rate for Poisson-distributed\nbackground. By adding a spatial penalty term to the definition of RTS, one can\nalso reject spatially-correlated backgrounds such as the ones due to spallation\nevents. Furthermore, the method is easy to implement in a real-time monitoring\nsystem as RTS can be computed recursively for successive events, and it can be\neasily adapted for detectors of all scales that may want to send prompt alerts\ne.g. through SNEWS 2.0 network.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 17 Mar 2021 15:41:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-10-20"}
